</caption>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" box="[199,305,1830,1857]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1830,1856]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">Spicules</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
Cortical triactines: Regular, actines are slightly conical and sharp. The actines are straight (paired actines: 123.1– 
<emphasis box="[228,291,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">150.7</emphasis>
±21.6–204.4/ 8.4– 
<emphasis box="[496,545,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">12.2</emphasis>
± 1.7–15.3 μm; unpaired actines: 81.5– 
<emphasis box="[985,1048,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">133.6</emphasis>
±23.2–180.0/ 8.9– 
<emphasis box="[1260,1323,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">122.3</emphasis>
±2.0–18.3 μm) (
<figureCitation box="[213,317,1938,1964]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1437,150,285]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
Subcortical tetractines: Giant, actines are slightly conical to conical and blunt. The paired actines are slightly curved (111.4– 
<emphasis box="[319,382,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">146.6</emphasis>
±21.8–192.1/ 10.8– 
<emphasis box="[601,650,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">14.5</emphasis>
± 2.0–19.2 μm). The unpaired actine is curved from the base to the tip (93.9– 
<emphasis box="[224,285,150,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">116.7</emphasis>
±21.5–156.6/ 14.1– 
<emphasis box="[502,551,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">15.2</emphasis>
±1.1–16.9 μm). The apical actine is long and conical (174.3– 
<emphasis box="[1224,1287,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">228.3</emphasis>
±29.1–285.4/ 16.9– 
<emphasis box="[214,263,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">20.8</emphasis>
±2.2–26.3 μm) (
<figureCitation box="[445,548,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Fig. 13B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,150,285]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
Diactines: Large, sinuous along their length. Most of them have one of the tips blunt while the other is sharp (330.0– 
<emphasis box="[238,301,258,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">464.8</emphasis>
±89.6–632.6/ 9.0– 
<emphasis box="[506,555,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">18.9</emphasis>
±4.0–25.7 μm) (
<figureCitation box="[736,839,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Fig. 13C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
